    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-02-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-02-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="24"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d24">
                <head>24. National Security Study Memorandum 89<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d24fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1"
                            >RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, POL 19 SW AFR. Secret. Copies
                        were sent to the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the Director of
                        Central Intelligence.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-02-12">February 12, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of the Treasury</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Commerce</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>U.S. Policy for Southwest Africa</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed a study of U.S. policy on Southwest Africa (Namibia)
                    in light of <gloss target="#t_NSDM_1">NSDM</gloss> 38<note n="2" xml:id="d24fn2">
                        <ref target="#d23">Document 23</ref>.</note> and the United Nations Security
                    Council’s decision to establish an ad hoc subcommittee to recommend further
                    steps to carry out relevant <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> resolutions.<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d24fn3">For details on the establishment of the ad hoc
                        subcommittee (Resolution 276 of January 30), its recommendations, and
                        actions taken by the Security Council and General Assembly, see <hi
                            rend="italic">Yearbook of the United Nations, 1970</hi>, pp.
                        734–746.</note>
                </p>
                <p>This study should: <list>
                        <item>—briefly summarize past developments, the current situation, and
                            likely prospects both in Africa and the United Nations;</item>
                        <item>—examine U.S. interests and objectives;</item>
                        <pb facs="0110" n="71" xml:id="pg_71"/>
                        <item>—propose optional U.S. policy courses for the longer term, including
                            any specific proposals needed to implement them over the coming
                            months.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>This paper should be drafted by an ad hoc group chaired by a representative of
                    the Secretary of State including representatives of the action addressees of
                    this memorandum and of the Assistant to the President for National Security
                    Affairs.</p>
                <p>The paper should be submitted to the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Review
                    Group by February 20.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
